AGI - Uncertainty, long waits for the verification of private buildings and therefore housing, little information and partly also wrong. In Bagnoli, district of the western area of Naples after almost twenty-four hours from the strongest shock of the last forty years, of magnitude 4.4, occurred at 1:25 of March 13, in many have slept another night out, mostly in the cars, spending the evening looking for directions, especially after the first evictions.
&nbsp;
The first ten families were displaced last night, after the verification of firefighters and civil protection and for those who do not have an alternative place, or do not find hospitality with relatives or friends, "there is nothing, no indication neither from those who have carried out the checks nor from the municipal police who presides over" the building, declared inoperable, to prevent someone from entering. After repeated requests, a municipal police officer informs and reports that "there is a station dedicated to the census of the displaced at the former NATO base", but who went did not find it, and that the green number for emergencies "was not yet activated".
<div </div
It is not even clear where the reception area is equipped with beds. The same municipal policeman says that "there should be one near the Maradona Stadium", others speak of Via Acate, where it is the Municipality, "but there are only a few small towns". Meanwhile, the waiting under the buildings of the part of the Bagnoli district where more obvious damage has been recorded, is marked by uncertainty about the conditions of the apartments.
&nbsp;
Ms. Nunzia, oncological patient tells AGI that she has contacted 115 for more than 12 hours. "I said I'm oncological and I can't breathe dust. Because I have the problem with the lung. I want to know if my house is viable." Henry is one of the displaced, has heart problems: "They didn't give us any alternative accommodation. We are trying to figure out what to do, because at least what was said at the time, whatever happens, there are accommodation. There should be a welcome area, but I don't know where it is."
&nbsp;
Henry's house is on the top floor of the building cleared in via Morandi, "my daughter was sleeping, suddenly fell stones and the door did not open because it was blocked by the stones, we had to push, there was a cloud of dust, we were sick and we had to run".
&nbsp;
We immediately called the firefighters shortly after, we did it repeatedly also contacting directly that he was spiking in the street, where they fell kicks, but nothing. Until tonight nothing." Rising to take things, it was evident that the loft had collapsed between the house and the roof terrace. It is "a building that was maintained also in the structural profile - says to AGI his daughter Francesca - the earthquake was undulatory and sussultory, very strong. Now we don't know what to do. I went to the city but the president was not there; I called, but he did not answer me". People on the street, outraged and worried, often emphasizes, speaking of the institutions, "they say that they are ready, is never predictable but you know for a long time, they planned, but now what is the emergency where they are?"
&nbsp;
At the former NATO base, in the square in front of the entrance there are dozens of cars with families camped. Mrs. Tina is looking for information because "no one said anything." His house turned out to be agivable but he wants to know "if anything happens, instead of being in the middle of the road, we go to sleep somewhere". You don't think about coming home. "We're down to the building, because we're scared. If another strong shock happens, how do we do it? Yesterday was a panic."
&nbsp;
Mr. Domenico, who lives on horseback in the districts Fuorigrotta and Bagnoli, will not return home and has decided to go to the waiting area set up by the Campania region in the former NATO base, "because there is fear of other shocks". "I have injuries in the house and I'm waiting for them to check to see if they're serious. After that, I think I'll go with my wife, who's panicked in Milan, where there are grandchildren."
&nbsp;
